      Now

      Kevin Arnovitz ESPN Staff Writer

      Kawhi Leonard, in the midst of the one of the most prolific individual runs in NBA postseason history, was a mere mortal in the first quarter before erupting in the second. He has 13 points, 10 rebounds, and three assists at intermission, punctuating the half with a driving slam on the Raptors' final possession. His Raptors' supporting cast assembled one of its best halves of the postseason. Pascal Siakam has returned to form (15 points), while still nursing a right calf contusion. Kyle Lowry has been both scorer and playmaker (11 points and four assists). Danny Green has been accurate from distance (11 points, 3-for-3 from beyond the arc). And Serge Ibaka enjoyed his best half of the series (six points on three field goals and three stitches after getting hit by Leonard unintentionally in the first quarter). Halftime: Toronto 64, Philadelphia 43.

      Malcolm Brogdon is listed as out on the NBA Injury Report for Game 5 between the Bucks and Celtics. The Bucks can still update Brogdon's status. They have until an hour before tip off to finalize the active/inactive list.

      Kevin Arnovitz ESPN Staff Writer

      Though Pascal Siakam is still nursing a right calf contusion, he gave the Raptors nine points in the first quarter, including a couple of 3-pointers. Kyle Lowry has been aggressive early, and added nine points. Joel Embiid, who is suffering from an upper respiratory infections, has been largely ineffective: 5 points (2-4 FG), but with three ugly turnovers. Toronto 27, Philadelphia 26.
